President Trump visited Kenosha, Wisconsin, to show his support for the community after it was hit by anti-police and anti-American riots. He commended law enforcement and the National Guard for their efforts in restoring peace and order. The President was joined by Attorney General Bill Barr and other officials, including local politicians and business owners affected by the riots. He expressed his commitment to helping Kenosha rebuild and announced financial support for law enforcement and small businesses. The President also addressed the issue of police violence, stating that while there may be some "bad apples," the majority of police officers are honorable and courageous public servants. He emphasized the need to support law enforcement and condemned the dangerous anti-police rhetoric. The President also discussed the possibility of sending federal agents to cities like Portland to address the ongoing violence and unrest. The article includes remarks from various officials and pastors who were present during the President's visit.